President Cyril Ramaphosa government does not agree with the recent decisions for South African Airways (SAA) by business rescue practitioners. . #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Plans to cut some of South African Airways' (SAA) domestic and international routes are aimed at making the airline sustainable and free from government funding after restructuring, experts appointed to try to rescue the company said on Sunday. State-owned SAA entered a form of bankruptcy protection in December and is fighting for its survival. READ: Labour unions not consulted on SAA flight cancellations The rescue specialists said on Thursday that SAA would cease flights to Durban, East London and Port Elizabeth from 29 February, as well as cutting some international routes, as part of efforts to conserve cash and make the airline more attractive to potential equity partners. President Cyril Ramaphosa said on Friday his government did not agree with plans to cut some of SAA's domestic routes, plunging rescue efforts for the cash-strapped carrier into uncertainty. READ: Government does not agree with SAA decisions “We recognise the concerns raised, especially around the domestic routes," SAA business rescue practitioners Les Matuson and Siviwe Dongwana said in a statement. "We will continue to engage with stakeholders, with a commitment to include inputs into the final business rescue plan, which is due to be published by the end of this month.” READ: SAA: Several domestic and international routes closed Under South African company law, the business rescue team is entitled to take decisions that are deemed necessary to turn a distressed company around, independently of government. In theory, it could ignore the government's objections. SAA is among several South African state entities -- including power company Eskom -- that are mired in financial crisis after nearly a decade of mismanagement.